.TH CAPSULE 1 "2026-02-24" "capsule" "User Commands"
.
.SH NAME
capsule \- execute a command inside a Linux network namespace
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B capsule
.I netns
.I command
.RI [ args \&.\|.\|.]
.br
.B capsule list
.RB [ \-v ]
.br
.B capsule status
.RB [ \-v ]
.I netns
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B capsule
enters the network namespace identified by
.I netns
and executes
.I command
inside it.
It is installed with
.B cap_sys_admin,cap_dac_read_search,cap_setpcap+ep
file capabilities (via
.BR setcap (8))
rather than as a setuid-root binary.
.PP
The sequence of operations is:
.IP 1. 3
Verify the caller is not root (UID\~0).
.IP 2.
Open
.I netns
with
.B O_PATH
(no read access through the fd) and verify via
.BR fstatfs (2)
that it is a network namespace
.RB ( NSFS_MAGIC ).
Drop
.B cap_dac_read_search
from the effective and permitted sets immediately after.
.IP 3.
If
.IR /etc/netns/ name /resolv.conf
exists, and
.I name
is a simple non-empty basename (not
.BR . ,
.BR .. ,
or containing
.RB \(aq / \(aq),
create a fully private mount namespace
.RB ( MS_PRIVATE )
and bind-mount the file over
.I /etc/resolv.conf
for DNS isolation.
.IP 4.
Call
.BR setns (2)
with
.B CLONE_NEWNET
to enter the namespace.
.IP 5.
Drop
.BR cap_sys_admin ,
.BR cap_dac_read_search ,
and
.B cap_setpcap
from the capability bounding set via
.BR prctl (2)
.BR PR_CAPBSET_DROP .
.RB ( PR_CAPBSET_DROP
requires
.B cap_setpcap
in the effective set, so this precedes the capability clear below.)
.IP 6.
Clear all capabilities: effective, permitted, inheritable, and ambient.
.IP 7.
.BR execvp (3)
the requested command with the original UID/GID and unmodified environment.
.PP
Because
.B execvp
replaces the
.B capsule
process, the child's exit status propagates directly to the caller.
.
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
.B list
List all named network namespaces found in
.IR /var/run/netns .
With
.BR \-v ,
also display the processes running inside each namespace.
All capabilities are dropped at entry; this subcommand requires none.
.
.TP
.B status
Show the network interfaces and running processes for a single namespace.
The
.I netns
argument accepts the same short name or full path as the exec form.
All capabilities are dropped after the
.BR setns (2)
call in interface enumeration completes.
.B \-v
is accepted and reserved; status always shows full detail.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.I netns
Either a short namespace name or a full path.
If the argument contains no
.RB \(aq / \(aq,
capsule constructs
.I /var/run/netns/<name>
and uses that path.
Full paths are used directly, so
.IR /var/run/netns/vpn ,
.IR /proc/<pid>/ns/net ,
and similar paths work as-is.
.
.TP
.I command
Name or path of the program to execute.
Searched via
.B PATH
if not an absolute path.
.
.TP
.RI [ args ]
Zero or more arguments forwarded verbatim to
.IR command .
.
.TP
.B \-v
Verbose mode.
For
.BR list :
show processes per namespace.
Accepted (and reserved) for
.BR status ,
which always shows full detail.
.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.B capsule
itself exits with status\~1 on any error before exec.
On success the exec form never returns \(em it becomes
.IR command ,
whose exit status is therefore the exit status seen by the caller.
The
.B list
and
.B status
subcommands exit 0 on success and 1 on error.
.
.SH ERRORS
Error messages are written to standard error with the prefix
.BR "capsule: " .
.
.TP
.B refusing to run as root (UID 0)
capsule was invoked as root.
Use
.BR "ip netns exec" (8)
or
.BR nsenter (1)
instead.
.
.TP
.IB netns-path ": No such file or directory"
The namespace file does not exist.
.
.TP
.IB netns-path ": not a network namespace"
The path exists but
.BR fstatfs (2)
did not return
.BR NSFS_MAGIC .
.
.TP
.B setns(CLONE_NEWNET): \fR...
.BR setns (2)
failed.
Common causes:
.B cap_sys_admin
is not set on the binary, or the caller does not have permission to enter this namespace.
.
.TP
.B cap_set_proc: \fR...
.BR libcap (3)
could not modify the capability sets.
.
.TP
.IB command ": No such file or directory"
.I command
was not found on
.BR PATH .
.
.SH SECURITY
.SS File capabilities
capsule is installed with
.BR "setcap 'cap_sys_admin,cap_dac_read_search,cap_setpcap+ep'" ,
not as a setuid-root binary.
Three capabilities are used:
.TP
.B cap_dac_read_search
Open the namespace file.
.BR "ip netns add" (8)
creates namespace files as nsfs bind mounts; nsfs does not implement
.IR setattr ,
so the files remain mode 000.
.B cap_dac_read_search
bypasses the DAC check.
It is dropped from E and P immediately after the file is opened \(em
before any mount or namespace operation.
.TP
.B cap_sys_admin
Call
.BR unshare (2)
and
.BR setns (2)
to enter the network namespace.
.TP
.B cap_setpcap
Drop
.BR cap_sys_admin ,
.BR cap_dac_read_search ,
and
.B cap_setpcap
itself from the capability bounding set.
.BR prctl (2)
.B PR_CAPBSET_DROP
requires this capability in the effective set.
.PP
All three capabilities are active only for the duration of the
.B capsule
process.
The child holds no capabilities after exec.
.
.SS Capability drop sequence
After
.BR setns ,
capsule performs the following in order:
.IP 1. 3
Drop
.BR cap_sys_admin ,
.BR cap_dac_read_search ,
and
.B cap_setpcap
from the bounding set via
.BR prctl (2)
.BR PR_CAPBSET_DROP .
This precedes the E/P/I clear because
.B PR_CAPBSET_DROP
requires
.B cap_setpcap
in the effective set.
.IP 2.
Clear the effective, permitted, and inheritable sets via
.BR cap_set_proc (3).
.IP 3.
Clear the ambient set via
.BR prctl (2)
.B PR_CAP_AMBIENT_CLEAR_ALL
(requires Linux\~4.3; silently ignored on older kernels).
.PP
A child that executes a binary carrying
.B cap_sys_admin
or
.B cap_dac_read_search
file capabilities cannot re-acquire those capabilities:
they are absent from the bounding set.
.
.SS Capability scope minimisation
.B cap_dac_read_search
is held for the minimum necessary scope.
In all paths it is dropped from E and P immediately after the namespace file
is opened \(em before
.BR unshare ,
.BR mount ,
or
.BR setns .
Only
.B cap_sys_admin
is held during namespace entry.
.PP
The
.B list
subcommand drops all capabilities at entry (it requires none).
The
.B status
subcommand drops
.B cap_dac_read_search
immediately after opening the namespace file, then drops all remaining
capabilities after interface enumeration completes, before process listing.
.
.SS Namespace fd
The namespace file is opened with
.B O_PATH | O_CLOEXEC
rather than
.BR O_RDONLY .
.B O_PATH
provides a file descriptor identifying the file without granting read access.
.BR fstatfs (2)
(since Linux\~3.12) and
.BR setns (2)
both accept
.B O_PATH
file descriptors.
.
.SS Input validation
The namespace basename used to locate
.I /etc/netns/<name>/resolv.conf
is validated: the name must be non-empty, must not be
.B .
or
.BR .. ,
and must contain no
.RB \(aq / \(aq
characters.
Paths that fail this check skip the DNS bind-mount silently.
.
.SS Mount isolation
When DNS isolation is active, the mount namespace is made fully private
.RB ( MS_PRIVATE )
before the bind-mount.
Mount events do not propagate in either direction between
capsule's private namespace and the parent mount namespace.
.
.SS Namespace access control
The namespace file is the access control boundary.
A user who cannot open the namespace file cannot enter the namespace.
The
.B cap_dac_read_search
file capability allows capsule to open mode-000 nsfs files;
the
.B NSFS_MAGIC
check ensures the opened fd is a real namespace, not an arbitrary file.
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /var/run/netns/\fIname\fR
Conventional location for named network namespaces, managed by
.BR ip-netns (8).
.
.TP
.I /etc/netns/\fIname\fR/resolv.conf
Per-namespace DNS configuration, written by
.BR capsule-netns-up (1).
Bind-mounted over
.I /etc/resolv.conf
when present and the namespace name passes validation.
.
.TP
.I /proc/\fIpid\fR/ns/net
Per-process network namespace file.
.
.SH EXAMPLES
Run Firefox inside a namespace named
.IR vpn :
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule vpn firefox
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Same using an explicit path:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule /var/run/netns/vpn firefox
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Open an interactive shell for debugging:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule vpn bash
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Check which external IP address is visible:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule vpn curl -s https://ifconfig.me
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Use the network namespace of a running process:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule /proc/1234/ns/net ip route show
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
List all named namespaces with processes:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule list -v
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Show interfaces and processes for a namespace:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule status vpn
.EE
.RE
.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR ip-netns (8),
.BR nsenter (1),
.BR setns (2),
.BR setcap (8),
.BR getcap (8),
.BR capabilities (7),
.BR network_namespaces (7)
.
.SH CAVEATS
.IP \(bu 2
Only the network namespace is changed.
The mount, PID, UTS, IPC, and user namespaces remain those of the calling process.
(When DNS isolation is active, a private mount namespace is also created,
but only to perform the
.I /etc/resolv.conf
bind-mount.)
.IP \(bu
The child starts with no capabilities.
Tools that require file capabilities
.RB ( cap_net_raw
for ping,
.B cap_net_bind_service
for privileged ports, etc.)
must have those capabilities set on their own binaries via
.BR setcap (8).
.IP \(bu
.B cap_setpcap
is part of the file capability set.
It is used only to perform bounding set drops and is itself dropped from
the bounding set before exec.
